nkers and activists who appear in Totality Inside Out reject this divisive logic altogether. Instead, they aim for a more expansive analysis of our contemporary moment to uncover connected sites of political struggle over racial and economic justice, materialist feminist and queer critique, climate change, and aesthetic value. The re-imagined account of capitalist totality that appears in this volume illuminates the material interlinkages between discrepant social phenomena, forms of oppression, and group histories, offering multiple entry points for readers who are interested in exploring how capitalism shapes integral relations within the social whole.Contributors: Brent Ryan Bellamy, Sarah Brouillette, Sarika Chandra, Chris Chen,Joshua Clover, Tim Kreiner, Arthur Scarritt, Zoe Sutherland, Marina Vishmidt  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aIntersectionality (Sociology). 0aMarginality, Social. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aMarxist theory.  acontemporary social movements.  acritical race studies.  afeminism.  alabor history.  aracial capitalism.  asocial reproduction theory.1 aBellamy, Brent Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellamy, Brent Ryan.1 aBrouillette, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouillette, Sarah.1 aChandra, Sarika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandra, Sarika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChandra, Sarika.1 aChen, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Chris.1 aClover, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClover, Joshua.1 aFloyd, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato